abstract={The challenge of decision-making under a changing climate in forestry has become a decent part in debates and in scientific discourses. This paper uses a socio-scientific approach to this topic. It is examined, if and how forest's actors identify risk due to forestry in climate change. For this purpose a four year lasting stakeholder project has been analysed. In this project, actors of the forest policy area were invited to discuss in a dialog forum central aspects of future forestry in Germany due to changing climate conditions and rising uncertainties. The group consisted of representatives of forest owners (state, municipal, private), conservation and environmental organizations as well as authorities, timber industry and research centers (Tab. 1). The debates took place as a round table; identification of topics to discuss was committed to stakeholders themselves (Tab. 2). All debates were lined by scientific or expert input. The actors have been identified before in an `analysis of discourse field', a method which helps to minimize subjective bias in determine a discourse arena. This turned out to be a reasonable method for identifying actors. For this paper all six workshops held in the project have been examined under aspects of risk research. It was examined, which risks are identified by stakeholders concerning future forestry in a changing climate. Therefore, a category scheme has been established in accordance with principles of social science (openness, naturalistics), defining following risk types: physic, economic and social (Tab. 3). Analysis of the workshops showed, that especially physical and economical risks have been addressed by stakeholders. Also addressed but not as prominently have been aspects of social risks. Concerning identified physical risks (loss of trees, diseases, etc.) actors agreed due to urgency. As economical risks, loss of cultivation area and investments in an unknown future have been identified. When social function