funding_text={I had the opportunity and honor to work closely with David Pimentel for more than a decade in the late eighties and the nineties. Undoubtedly, David's intuition for environmental accounting, his enthusiasm for research and teaching, and his active engagement with emerging environmental concerns shaped my research career. Only now, after two decades of struggling with narrow-minded environmental researchers and policymakers, am I able to fully appreciate the extent and relevance of David's work. His innate holistic and practical view of social-ecological systems permitted him to adopt a highly relevant system of quantitative characterization without pre-analytical conceptualization or formalizations. Whereas David dedicated his research career to exposing environmental concerns with numbers, I have spent most of mine framing David's insights in theoretical and conceptual terms thereby heavily drawing on complexity theory. In this way, I hope to have contributed to the due recognition of his work. This article builds on the work performed in the Horizon 2020 project ``Moving Towards Adaptive Governance in Complexity: Informing Nexus Security{''} (MAGIC). It could not possibly exist without the efforts and insights of the MAGIC consortium, and notably that of the UAB team. MAGIC was funded by the European Union's Horizon 2020 research and innovation program under Grant Agreement No. 689669. I also wish to acknowledge financial support by the Spanish Ministry of Science and Innovation (MICINN) through the ``Maria de Maeztu{''} program for Units of Excellence (CEX2019-000940-M). This work reflects my view only; the funding agencies are not responsible for any use that may be made of the information it contains.},
